# Webtoon Scroll Camera System

## The Core Problem

Manhwa/webtoon images are tall vertical strips (~709×2058, ratio ≈ 1:3). The current pipeline was designed for manga layouts:

| Current Pipeline Step | What it assumes | What webtoon actually needs |
|---|---|---|
| **panelSplitter** | Clear gutters (black/white lines) separate panels | Seamless artwork, no gutters — art flows continuously |
| **cameraDirector** | Independent focus regions to zoom into | A **scroll path** — camera flows top→bottom through the strip |
| **videoRenderer** (multi-shot) | Cut between static zoom shots | **Continuous smooth motion** — scroll + zoom + pause |
| **Ken Burns fallback** | Center-crop + slight zoom | Misses 60%+ of the strip content |

The fundamental mismatch: **manga is a grid of independent panels; webtoon is a single continuous vertical canvas**. We need a completely different camera system for the webtoon format, toggled by the user.

---

## Proposed Changes

### 1. Format Toggle — Frontend

The user picks **Manga** or **Manhwa/Webtoon** when creating or configuring a project. This is a simple toggle in three places:

#### [MODIFY] [RenderSettings.jsx](file:///c:/Users/parvi/Documents/animereels/client/src/components/RenderSettings.jsx)

Add a **Format Type** toggle section at the top, before Duration/Detail:

```jsx
const FORMAT_OPTIONS = [
  {
    value: 'manga',
    label: '📖 Manga',
    description: 'Grid layout with distinct panels. Camera zooms into each panel.',
  },
  {
    value: 'webtoon',
    label: '📱 Manhwa / Webtoon',
    description: 'Tall vertical strips. Camera scrolls top-to-bottom with zoom highlights.',
  },
];
```

Uses the same `detailCard` / `detailCardActive` styling already in place for the Detail Level selector — visually consistent, zero new CSS needed.

Adds `format` + `onFormatChange` props alongside the existing `duration` / `detail` props.

---

#### [MODIFY] [ProjectWizard.jsx](file:///c:/Users/parvi/Documents/animereels/client/src/pages/ProjectWizard.jsx)

